---
import AnimatedHero from "../components/AnimatedHero.astro";
import MarketingShell from "../components/MarketingShell.astro";
---

<MarketingShell
  title="AI code review with receipts"
  description="Warden is an AI code review CLI that runs deterministic tools, verifies external claims, and uses an LLM only for triage."
>
  <main>
    <section class="hero-section">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">AI code review CLI</p>
        <h1>Warden</h1>
        <p class="hero-lede">
          Deterministic tools produce the facts. Citable sources verify external claims. The LLM
          gets the narrow job it is good at: triage, wording, and ordering.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button primary" href="/docs/" data-astro-prefetch>Read docs</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="/examples/" data-astro-prefetch>View output</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <AnimatedHero />
    </section>

    <section class="proof-strip" aria-label="Review contract">
      <p><strong>TSC and ESLint</strong><span>structured local findings</span></p>
      <p><strong>npm audit and OSV</strong><span>CVE claims with receipts</span></p>
      <p><strong>LLM formatter</strong><span>triage without free-form invention</span></p>
      <p><strong>CommentSet JSON</strong><span>ready for future wrappers</span></p>
    </section>

    <section class="home-band">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">What makes it different</p>
        <h2>Warden keeps the reviewer honest.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article>
          <span class="feature-kicker">01</span>
          <h3>Facts come from tools.</h3>
          <p>
            TypeScript, ESLint, duplication checks, dependency audit output, and deterministic
            detectors are the evidence layer. The model receives claims; it does not invent them.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span class="feature-kicker">02</span>
          <h3>External claims need receipts.</h3>
          <p>
            Vulnerabilities are cross-checked through OSV before they appear. Unverified advisories
            are dropped instead of laundered into confident prose.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span class="feature-kicker">03</span>
          <h3>The output is a contract.</h3>
          <p>
            Every run returns a typed CommentSet with stable ids, tiers, categories, citations, and
            degraded-worker metadata future web or bot surfaces can consume.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="workflow-band">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Pipeline</p>
        <h2>Local first, citation first.</h2>
      </div>
      <ol class="workflow">
        <li><span>Detect</span><p>Find the JS/TS workspace shape and diff scope.</p></li>
        <li><span>Run</span><p>Execute deterministic tools and prune known noise before review.</p></li>
        <li><span>Verify</span><p>Check dependency and API claims against citable sources.</p></li>
        <li><span>Format</span><p>Ask the LLM to rank, clarify, and render the review.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="closing-band">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Current shape</p>
        <h2>Built as a CLI. Ready for wrappers later.</h2>
        <p>
          The public site is intentionally static: docs, examples, design notes, and rendered
          fixtures. The interactive triage app and GitHub bot remain separate future surfaces.
        </p>
      </div>
      <a class="button primary" href="/design/" data-astro-prefetch>Read design notes</a>
    </section>
  </main>
</MarketingShell>
